Introduction:

This is an individual project for Airbnb NYC rental price prediction using over 90 vairables on the property, host, and past reviews. I will use Linear Regression and Trees to create models predicting Airbnb rental price using attributes in the given dataset. At the end of this report, I will be comparing the prediction result based on different techniques, and a list of submission will be attached for reference.

2. Preparing the Data for Analysis

Firstly, remove the useless data.

Since the real-world data is very dirty and unorganized, the first thing is to remove thoes that are obviously useless for us or they are too dirty to use. I defined them as “removable” based the following conditions:

  1. Spread out too wide

  2. Implausible or illogical values

  3. Features have single value for all rows that do not affact the result

# When I look at the variables, the following seemed useless to me, so that I can remove them

6. Discussion

Overview

In this Kaggle Competition, I spent 70% of the time on data exploration and data preparation, including missing value imputation, outliers removal as well as feature selection. I started from building simple linear models and train the model to make predictions. Moreover, then, based on the assumption of linear regression, I tried to test if there are outliers and removed them from the train data set, which improved the model a little bit.

Next, I plotted the distribution of price in the train data set and noticed that it is. Therefore, I tried to do log transformation to make it normal distributed. After testing in the model, I realized that log transformation does lower the Residual Error. However, it also reduces the R square.

Other than linear regression, I also used Random Forest and Boosting to train the model. The results showed that Trees were a better choice than a Linear model in this case.

Overall, the scores I got were not perfect. Instead of model selection, I should have spent more time on feature engineering, and pay more attention to the interactive terms.

Limitation

One of the pressing issues that I had in this competition was Overfitting. Because when I added more predictors in my models and tried to improve the accuracy, the results sometimes even got worst. Generally speaking, it is because the predictor I used has too many different values/too many factor levels. Besides, I may have included many predictors that were highly correlated and overlapped.

Another issue is the way I dealt with Categorical data, such as text and character. A lot of them were just simply removed in the first place.
